TY  - JOUR
AU  - Anand, Amber
AU  - Irvine, Paul
AU  - Puckett, Andy
AU  - Venkataraman, Kumar
T1  - Performance of Institutional Trading Desks: An Analysis of Persistence in Trading Costs
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhr110
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 2
SP  - 557
EP  - 598
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Using a proprietary dataset of institutional investors' equity transactions, we document that institutional trading desks can sustain relative performance over adjacent periods. We find that trading-desk skill is positively correlated with the performance of the institution's traded portfolio, suggesting that institutions that invest resources in developing execution abilities also invest in generating superior investment ideas. Although some brokers can deliver better executions consistently over time, our analysis suggests that trading-desk skill is not limited to a selection of better brokers. We conclude that the trade implementation process is economically important and can contribute to relative portfolio performance.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhr110
ER  - 



