TY  - JOUR
AU  - Miller, Darius P.
AU  - Reisel, Natalia
T1  - Do Country-level Investor Protections Affect Security-level Contract Design? Evidence from Foreign Bond Covenants
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhr097
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 2
SP  - 408
EP  - 438
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article studies the ability of security-level contracts to substitute for poor country-level investor protections. Using a cross-country sample of restrictive covenants, we find that bond contacts are more likely to include covenants when creditor protection laws are weak. Further, the use of restrictive covenants in weak creditor protection countries is associated with a lower cost of debt. We also find that strong country-level shareholder rights are not necessarily harmful to bondholders. Overall, the findings suggest that issuers and investors can create international contracts that overcome some of the deficiencies of country-level investor protections and facilitate access to external finance.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhr097
ER  - 



